<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTY LIBRARY'S SUMMER READING PROGRAM A SUCCESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Orange County library officials are proclaiming their summer reading program a 
success, saying that the storytelling sessions and musical performances have 
drawn more than 12,000 children during the past three months. 
</P>
<P>
 The theme of this year's program, "Western Tales and Trails," highlights books 
and songs about cowboys, gold and living in the Old West. 
</P>
<P>
 The reading series runs through Aug. 27. Children and their parents can still 
catch several performances at library branches around the county. 
</P>
<P>
 Today , stagecoach rides will be offered at 2:30 p.m. at La Palma Library, 
7842 Walker St. 
</P>
<P>
 On Saturday, Samba N'Go Pop will give two musical performances at the San Juan 
Capistrano regional library, 31495 El Camino Real. The performances will be at 
7 and 9 p.m. On Aug. 27, that library will present Latin jazz concerts at 7 and 
9 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 On Wednesday, K.C. & Company will perform cowboy songs and stories at 2 p.m. 
at the Laguna Beach library, 363 Glenneyre St. 
</P>
<P>
 The reading program has been going on for three months. As of mid-July, 12,500 
children had taken part in activities, county library spokeswoman Cheryl Pruett 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 "The goal is to encourage children to read and look at the library as a source 
for reading and entertaining and exploring the world," Pruett said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
