<P>
 Oil Imports Set Record in July: U.S. imports of crude oil and its derivatives 
toppled a 17-year-old record last month, though overall demand for petroleum 
products declined. The import level, reported by the American Petroleum 
Institute, illustrates a well-established trend in the U.S. economy: Business 
and individuals are becoming increasingly dependent on foreign oil.Taken 
together, imports of crude oil and petroleum products in July, at an average of 
10.059 million barrels daily, were up 9.1% from the previous July, according to 
the API, the trade group for major U.S.-based oil companies. Imports last month 
accounted for about 58% of domestic demand, another record. It was also the 
first time imports exceeded the level of 10 million barrels a day.UNITED STA 
</P>
