CITY HALL JOURNAL: LONG BEACH; PORT DIRECTOR RECEIVES 5% SALARY INCREASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Long Beach harbor commissioners have approved a 5% pay raise for the port's 
chief administrator, making him the second-highest-paid city official. 
</P>
<P>
 The five-member commission voted 4-1 last week to raise Executive Director 
Steven R. Dillenbeck's salary from $131,841 to $138,393.  
</P>
<P>
 With the increase, Dillenbeck ranks only behind City Manager James C. Hankla, 
who earns $155,721 a year. Dillenbeck, 54, has headed the port of Long Beach 
since 1991. He has been with the agency since 1987. 
</P>
<P>
 Even with the pay increase, Dillenbeck makes less than some other port 
directors on the West Coast, including Los Angeles, a port spokeswoman said. 
Commissioners gave Dillenbeck a 3% pay raise in July, 1993. 
</P>
